I would disagree with you: rightist are right when they call brutalist buildings in Western cities "tumors", because for proper brutalism the entire area needs to be built in the style, otherwise it can never fit in properly . But rightists are wrong on brutalism being bad when..

properly executed. I think you are wrong about "luxurious" brutalism - I think it always feels artificial, fake - like a man who always makes sure to appear careless and spends too much time dressing himself n√©glig√©, making hair messy on purpose etc.

To properly understand brutalism you need to be aware of how deeply spiritual it is and what immense psychological effects living in it has. In brutalist cities a specific kind of culture manifests itself, a specific type of "person". A new mythology develops, a very unique one

I love the first - it is a "closed" brutalist space though. IMO it just needs more trees and to let them grow tall. The second is meh; the fourth I dislike. It would look absolutely incredible in an Eastern European town, but next to the cute smol church it just looks vulgar 2 me

The interior one is very weird to me because this is not at all what I associate with brutalism, far more like bourgeoisie nord minimalism. Brutalist interior as I know it is far more maximalist - I will snap you a pic of a good soviet era apartment next time i go to my grandma's

These are closer to what I have experienced and what I actually love. Just walking home from school during the early winter night and the giant buildings towering over me, looking at the windows, the stars above - it is very hard to describe it in non-expressionist prose

You feel very small, but you also feel part of something greater. There are seemingly random winds, bad street lighting, noises - some housewife yelling at her drunk husband, there are smells. You lose track of time, it truly hypnotizes you

Bad thing is that EU-adjacent libs here try to "modernize" the buildings by painting over them in bright "happy" colours, using Western styles for newer buildings, replacing cosmos-themed playgrounds with safe EU ones. It disgusts me. But things will revert with time, as they do.

One time I climbed to a ghetto Soviet building's 15th floor, and there was, next to the staircase to the rooftop, a single clothes-washing tub, filled with sand, and a sign that said "Do not shit in the tub". There was also a large human shit in the tub.
